Building the Model we define input shape, layers, Activation function

Creating a Layer for Resizing and Normalization(Rescaling)
Before we feed our images to network, we should be resizing it to the desired size. Moreover, to improve model performance, we should normalize the image pixel value (keeping them in range 0 and 1 by dividing by 256). This should happen while training as well as inference. Hence we can add that as a layer in our Sequential Model.
You might be thinking why do we need to resize (256,256) image to again (256,256). You are right we don't need to but this will be useful when we are done with the training and start using the model for predictions. At that time somone can supply an image that is not (256,256) and this layer will resize it.
resize_and_rescale = tf.keras.Sequential([
  layers.experimental.preprocessing.Resizing(IMAGE_SIZE, IMAGE_SIZE),
  layers.experimental.preprocessing.Rescaling(1./255),
])
Data Augmentation
Data Augmentation is applying transformations to existing data samples to create new, varied versions while preserving their labels.
Ex: Rotation, Flipping, Cropping, Zooming, Brightness, contrast, Noise addition, Colour shifting
It is needed when we have less data, this boosts the accuracy of our model by augmenting the data.
data_augmentation = tf.keras.Sequential([
  layers.experimental.preprocessing.RandomFlip("horizontal_and_vertical"),
  layers.experimental.preprocessing.RandomRotation(0.2),   ])
Model Architecture
We use a CNN coupled with a Softmax activation in the output layer. We also add the initial layers for resizing, normalization and Data Augmentation.
input_shape = (BATCH_SIZE, IMAGE_SIZE, IMAGE_SIZE, CHANNELS)
n_classes = 3

model = models.Sequential([
    resize_and_rescale,
    layers.Conv2D(32, kernel_size = (3,3), activation='relu', input_shape=input_shape),
    layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)),
    layers.Conv2D(64,  kernel_size = (3,3), activation='relu'),
    layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)),
    layers.Conv2D(64,  kernel_size = (3,3), activation='relu'),
    layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)),
    layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'),
    layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)),
    layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'),
    layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)),
    layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'),
    layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)),
    layers.Flatten(),
    layers.Dense(64, activation='relu'),
    layers.Dense(n_classes, activation='softmax'),
])

model.build(input_shape=input_shape)


Compiling the Model we set optimizer, loss function, metrics
Its like setting rules & tools for training.
We use adam Optimizer, SparseCategoricalCrossentropy for losses, accuracy as a metric
model.compile(
    optimizer='adam',
    loss=tf.keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(from_logits=False),
    metrics=['accuracy']
)
	

Optimizer: how the model learns & updates weights
Adam AdaGrad & RMSProp, adjusts learning rates dynamically
Loss function: how errors are measured
           used for multi-class classification where labels are integers (not one-hot encoded)
Metrics: how performance is tracked
Train the Model (model.fit)
model.fit() is the training function — it makes your model learn from the data by adjusting its internal weights over multiple passes (called epochs).

history = model.fit(
    train_ds,
    batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,  #no of samples processed before model updates its weights
    validation_data=val_ds,
    verbose=1,
    epochs=50,
)

Smaller batches = slower but more accurate
larger batches = faster but may miss details.
More epochs = more learning, but risk of overfitting if too many.



